Alternative forms[edit]

  • robō, rubō, rupō

Etymology[edit]

Borrowed from Frankish *raubōn (“to rob, plunder”).

Pronunciation[edit]

  • (Ecclesiastical) IPA(key): /ˈrau̯.bo/, [ˈrau̯.bɔ]

Verb[edit]

raubō (present infinitive raubāre, perfect active raubāvī, supine raubātum); first conjugation[1]

  1. (Medieval Latin) I rob, plunder

Descendants[edit]

  • Old French: rober, robber, robier
    • Middle French: rober, robber
      • ⇒ Middle French: desrober, dérober
        • French: dérober
        • → English: disrobe
    • → Middle English: robben, roben
      • English: rob
  • Iberian:
    • Asturian: robar
    • Old Portuguese: roubar, rroubar
      • Galician: roubar
      • Portuguese: roubar
    • Spanish: robar
  • Italian: rubare
  • Old Occitan: raubar
    • Catalan: robar
    • Occitan: raubar
